    "rationale": "This is the classic textbook example of the Fries rearrangement, showing the conversion of phenyl acetate to 2-hydroxyacetophenone. It clearly demonstrates the migration of an acyl group from a phenolic oxygen to an ortho position on the aromatic ring, which is the defining characteristic of this reaction family. The use of aluminum chloride as a Lewis acid catalyst is also canonical for the thermal Fries rearrangement.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses the simplest possible aromatic system (phenyl) and acyl group (acetyl) to avoid overlap with more complex named reactions involving substituted arenes or specific functional groups. It avoids motifs like diazo groups, ring expansions, or radical initiators that could cause collisions with other reaction families. The core transformation is a simple acyl migration on a phenol ester, which is highly specific to the Fries rearrangement."
  }
}
